    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm looking at my student loan amortization schedule and i'm kinda confused. i've been making my monthly payments on time every month but the principal balance is barely even going down. can you explain how the interest actually gets calculated each month? like, why does it feel like so much of my money is just disappearing instead of hitting the actual loan amount?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The interest calculation can be a bit tricky, but I'll break it down for you. You see, the interest is calculated as a percentage of the outstanding principal balance, and it's usually compounded monthly. This means that the interest is added to the principal balance at the end of each month, so the next month's interest is calculated on the new, higher balance. It's a bit like a never-ending game of \"gobbling up\" your payments, where the interest is the sneaky, hungry goblin that keeps growing and growing, making it harder to pay off the loan. \n\nIn your case, it's possible that the interest rate is higher than you thought, or that the loan has a longer repayment term than you anticipated. This can cause the interest to balloon, making it seem like your payments are disappearing into thin air. But don't worry, you're still making progress, even if it doesn't feel like it. Just keep in mind that the interest is like a pesky little goblin that's always lurking in the shadows, waiting to pounce on your hard-earned cash. \n\nTo give you a better idea, let's say you have a $10,000 loan with a 6% interest rate",
      "source": "target",
